04355nam a22005535i 9780520352957DE-B159720240306123113.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t19881988cau    fo  d z      eng d  a97805203529577 a10.1525/97805203529572doi  a(DE-B1597)648217  a(OCoLC)1414457199  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  acaucUS-CA 7aSCI0000002bisacsh1 aOsterbrock/Gustafson, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aEye on the Sky :bLick Observatory's First Century /cOsterbrock/Gustafson; ed. by Donald E. Osterbrock, John R. Gustafson, Shiloh Unruh. 1aBerkeley, CA : bUniversity of California Press, c[1988] 4cÂ©1988  a1 online resource (326 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPreface -- t1 His tombstone is a telescope -- t2 The greatest astronomer of his time -- t3 A son of the Confederacy -- t4 The telescope comes to the mountain -- t5 Into the ocean of science -- t6 The great I am -- t7 Adonais -- t8 The creative scientist who became a factory manager -- t9 In the shadow of the moon -- t10 Leuschner's legacy -- t11 Double-star observer -- t12 The last of the first -- t13 Second largest telescope in the world -- t14 Santa Cruz -- t15 One hundred years on -- tReferences -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe world's first mountain-top observatory and America's first big-science research center, Lick Observatory exemplifies astronomy's dramatic development in the past century. A dedicated Confederate naval officer and his jack-of-all-trades foreman used the bequest of a miserly California eccentric to transform an isolated mountain peak into the world's premier research observatory. Its first staff included a director from West Point and three of the outstanding astronomers of their time. Since its dedication in 1888, Lick Observatory has been the site of many of the most important discoveries in astronomy.Eye on the Sky presents Lick Observatory from the point of view of the people who breathed life into its giant telescopes. Their community was both constant and constantly transformed, shaped by workers famous and unknown who made it their home. The authors also explain in terms anyone can understand the laboratory advances that were adapted to telescopes to make them more powerful, and the conceptual breakthroughs that discoveries at the telescope helped bring about.The men and women who went to the top of Mount Hamilton in search of greater knowledge of the skies helped to change our conception of the universe and our place in it . They were people with personal and political lives as well as scientific careers, and their story illuminates a time and a place where foundations were laid for the discoveries of the next century.  aIssued also in print.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 4aGeneral. 4aScience. 7aSCIENCE / General.2bisacsh1 aGustafson, John R., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aOsterbrock, Donald E., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aUnruh, Shiloh, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Package Archive Pre-2000z97831106353480 cprintz978052026869240uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/978052035295740uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520352957423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520352957/original  a978-3-11-063534-8  University of California Press Package Archive Pre-2000b2000  aEBA_UCA_YUP  aGBV-deGruyter-alles